nary, micro-historical approach remains a fundamental aspect of Holocaust research, and can provide a theoretical framework for future studies.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHolocaust. 4aIntegrierte Geschichte. 4aMikrogeschichte. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aHolocaust.  aintegrated history.  amicro-history.1 aBaker, Emily-Rose, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBirch, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnesoeur, Frédéric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonnesoeur, Frédéric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDaelen, Veerle Vanden, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickson, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDreyfus, Jean-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerenc, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFubel, Janine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGil, Idit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGondek, Abby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirsh, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuhák, Heléna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones-Amin, Holly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Dana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlacsmann, Borbála, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlei, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemberg, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo